 {"id":"bd-264","title":"Implement Session.merge() for detached objects","description":"## Description

Merge detached objects back into session.

## Python Behavior

```python
# Object from previous session or serialized
detached_user = User(id=1, name='Updated Name')

# Merge into current session
attached_user = session.merge(detached_user)

# attached_user is now tracked, changes will be persisted
```

Key behavior:
1. If object with same PK in session, update it and return session's copy
2. If not in session, query DB and merge attributes
3. If not in DB, treat as new (will INSERT)
4. Recursively merge relationships if load=True

## Rust Implementation

```rust
impl Session {
    pub async fn merge<M: Model>(
        &mut self,
        cx: &Cx,
        model: M,
        load: bool,
    ) -> Outcome<M, Error> {
        let pk = model.primary_key_value();

        // 1. Check identity map
        if let Some(existing) = self.identity_map.get_mut::<M>(&pk) {
            // Update existing with new values
            existing.merge_from(&model);
            return Ok(existing.clone());
        }

        if load {
            // 2. Check database
            if let Some(mut db_model) = self.get::<M>(cx, pk).await? {
                db_model.merge_from(&model);
                self.add(db_model.clone());
                return Ok(db_model);
            }
        }

        // 3. Treat as new
        self.add(model.clone());
        Ok(model)
    }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Merges into existing session object if present
- [ ] Loads from DB and merges if load=True
- [ ] Treats as new if not in DB
- [ ] Recursively merges relationships
- [ ] Returns the session-attached version

